(3378, 3, '2016-07-22 12:50:42', '2016-07-22 12:50:42', '[tg_header title="Raft, Kayak, Explore" subtitle="A Wet &amp; Wild Family-Friendly Adventure"]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSpringing from the high slopes of Machhapuchhre, "Fishtail Mountain," the lower Seti River offers superb forest scenery and gentle rapids.\n\nStudent groups, families, with children, or adults looking for a low-key adventure will enjoy relaxing along the sandy beaches, swimming in the warm water, and exploring the riverbanks. Wildlife enthusiasts will be delighted by the variety of animals found in this lush river basin.\n\nThe Seti offers a two-day rafting adventure just a short drive from Pokhara (52 km) or Kathmandu (154 km). Combine the Seti River Adventure with a wildlife safari in Chitwan National Park or a Jalbire Canyoning Expedition before continuing onward to your next adventure.\n\nDeluxe trips are available and may appeal to honeymooners, couples celebrating an important anniversary, or anyone wishing to travel in style. Enjoy candlelit dinners on the beach and a glass of wine under the star-swept sky of the Nepali night.\n\n[tg_header title="Quick Look" subtitle="Adventure Overview"]\n\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>February - May, September - January (or choose the rainy season for Monsoon Blast)\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>2 days\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Grade 2-3\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Appropriate for beginners, families with children, retirees, honeymooners, student groups &amp; organizations\n<strong>Put-in: </strong>Damauli Bridge\n<strong>Take-out: </strong>Ghaighat (low water) or Narayanghat (high water)\n<strong>Transportation: </strong>Private van from Kathmandu or Pokhara\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Trekking, rafting, sightseeing, Chitwan wildlife safari\n<strong>Options: </strong>Deluxe or Standard Trip\n<strong>Accommodations: </strong>Tented camping\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[tg_header title="Adventure Program" subtitle="2 Days of Scenic, Splashy Fun"]\n\n[tg_program title="Arrival" place="Kathmandu"]Take a deep breath and prepare to confront the confusion of Tribhuvan International Airport. After clearing immigration and customs, hang on to your gear and push past the would-be airport porters to the passenger pick-up area outside the building. This can be pretty confusing, with taxi drivers looking for fares, hotel touts desperately seeking customers, and a large crowd just milling around - welcome to Asia!\n\nDon''t worry, a Nepalaya Explorer representative will be there to meet you at the airport and escort you to your hotel. In the afternoon, you will have time to venture into the bustle of this amazing city for your first taste of Kathmandu. Walking around this ancient city is like being in the world''s biggest outdoor museum. We recommend a good guide book (available at a reasonable price at any of Kathmandu''s many book shops), then grabbing a taxi or a rickshaw, or setting out on foot to visit some of the incredible temples, stupas, and squares that make up this most vibrant of capitals. From observing prayer wheels turning at the Buddhist stupa Bouddhanath, to perhaps gaining a glimpse of the Living Goddess in Durbar Square, there are endless ways to pass the day. A great way to finish it off is people watching, cold drink in hand, on one of the many terrace cafes.\n\nAt 6 pm, we''ll meet for a pre-departure briefing, then head off to one of Kathmandu''s finer restaurants to share a meal.[/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title="Day 1" place="Seti River"]AM: Rise early and gather your things. Nepalaya Explorer''s driver will shuttle you to the put-in (4 hours from Kathmandu or 2 hours from Pokhara), where your river crew is waiting to welcome you. Your trip leader introduces you to the crew and the rafting equipment, then everyone is outfitted with rafting gear. The trip leader and safety kayaker brief the group about whitewater safety and paddling technique while the guides tie the equipment into the rafts. (This is quite a thing to witness - twenty years of running rivers have taught us a lot, not the least of which is loading a raft so the load stays put.)\n\nRafting the Seti with Nepalaya Explorer isn''t just a vacation. It''s an education in water sports as well as an exploration of the river highway - our guides make sure to explain the finer points of paddling in whitewater and teach you how to stay in the raft as it bucks through the rapids.\n\nSoon enough, we are navigating the scenic Seti River basin. The river is lined by white sand beaches, beyond which the lush forest slopes upwards. After a couple gentle rapids, it''s time for lunch. Then we''re back on the river, with more rapids to come before we reach our campsite. The camp is tastefully sculptured into a huge eddyline,  and high walls overlooking the Seti River. Beyond, behind the tents, the beach merges with a Gurung village.\n\nPM: Share a candlelit dinner with your family or fellow river guests. Enjoy a glass of wine under the stars before retiring into your tent to enjoy a well-earned rest.[/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title="Day 2" place="Seti River"]Awake to a hearty breakfast prepared by your guides. Will you take tea or coffee? We pack up camp, leaving only our footprints in the sand. This day, the Seti offers bigger rapids and more excitement, but is still appropriate for beginners. Following the confluence of the Seti and the Trisuli Rivers, the river widens substantially and the current picks up the pace. From here, we float easily with the current until we reach the take-out. Our crew divides in teams to prepare lunch and pack the gear. We take a couple of group photos with the crew. Till we meet again![/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title="Add-on Option #1" place="Canyoning"]If you''re still hungry for adventure when it''s time the get off the river, then the Jalbire Canyoning Adventure may be just up your alley. Located only 45 minutes upstream along the Trisuli River, Jalbire is one of the longest waterfalls in Nepal. This family-friendly canyoning experience can be customized to fit a group of any ability level. Visit the Jalbire Canyoning Adventure page or email us for more information.[/tg_program]\n\n[tg_program title="Add-on Option #2" place="Safari"]After getting off the river, keep heading South to Chitwan National Park, to finish off your trip with a stay at the luxurious Tiger Tops Lodge and Camp. Set in the heart of the park, the Lodge offers fantastic bird watching opportunities, not to mention occasional sightings of the Royal Bengal Tiger, rhino, and a rich array of other wildlife. Naturalists are on hand with their seemingly endless supply of knowledge to answer your queries.\n\nThe Lodge is made entirely of local materials and blends beautifully with its environment. Enjoy a range of activities, from elephant safaris to jungle walks, to plain old relaxing in the serene surroundings of the Lodge. Meals are all-inclusive and the menu includes delicious western as well as Nepali dishes. Accommodation is in spacious safari tents with twin beds and separate hot and cold showers.\n[/tg_program]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[tg_header title="Price Includes:" subtitle="Deluxe"]\n<ul>\n	<li>Licensed English-speaking local guides and safety kayakers, highly trained and safety certified to international standards in: Rescue 3 WRT, Nepal Red Cross CPR, High Peak First Aid, International Wilderness First-Aid, IRF trained, and highly knowledgable about the local area</li>\n	<li>High-quality, ISO certified rafting and kayaking equipment and full personal outfitting, including: paddles, helmets, PFDs (life jackets) dry tops, wetsuits (youth sizes available), dry bags, and pelican boxes for valuables such as cameras</li>\n	<li>Two nights at a *** hotel in Kathmandu, one day sightseeing in Kathmandu, airport pickup and drop-off</li>\n	<li>Camping accommodation, including: shelters, personal tents, air mattresses, sleeping bags, pillow, picnic umbrella, table and chairs, toilet tents</li>\n	<li>Three meals daily: a hearty breakfast, leisurely lunch, and dinner with a complementary glass of wine. While on the river, guides prepare traditional Nepali and western cuisine, made with fresh, organic ingredients.</li>\n	<li>Complementary beverages, including bottled water</li>\n	<li>Round trip transportation via private car</li>\n	<li>River permits</li>\n	<li>Village sightseeing</li>\n	<li>Adventure Industry standard first aid kits</li>\n</ul>\n[tg_header title="Price Includes:" subtitle="Standard"]\n<ul>\n	<li>Licensed English-speaking local guides and safety kayakers, highly trained and safety certified to international standards in: Rescue 3 WRT, Nepal Red Cross CPR, High Peak First Aid, International Wilderness First-Aid, IRF trained, and highly knowledgable about the local area</li>\n	<li>High-quality, ISO certified rafting and kayaking equipment and full personal outfitting, including: paddles, helmets, PFDs (life jackets) dry tops, wetsuits (youth sizes available), dry bags, and pelican boxes for valuables such as cameras</li>\n	<li>Two nights at at tourist hotel in Kathmandu, one day sightseeing in Kathmandu, airport pickup and drop-off</li>\n	<li>Camping accommodation, including: shelters, personal tents, air mattresses, sleeping bags, toilet tents</li>\n	<li>Three meals daily: a hearty breakfast, leisurely lunch, and dinner with a complementary glass of wine. While on the river, guides prepare traditional Nepali and western cuisine, made with fresh, organic ingredients.</li>\n	<li>Complementary beverages, including bottled water</li>\n	<li>Round trip transportation via private car</li>\n	<li>River permits</li>\n	<li>Village sightseeing</li>\n	<li>Adventure Industry standard first aid kits</li>\n</ul>\n[tg_header title="Price Does Not Include:"]\n<ul>\n	<li>International flights and associated taxes</li>\n	<li>Items of personal nature (toiletries, clothing, camera, etc.)</li>\n	<li>Alcohol and specialty beverages</li>\n	<li>Tips for porters and guides</li>\n	<li>Travel and health insurance</li>\n</ul>\n[tg_header title="What to Bring:"]\n<ul>\n	<li>Your sense of adventure (and humor!)</li>\n	<li>River shorts or swim costume</li>\n	<li>Chacos or similar sandals that secure your heal (trainers or sneakers are also suitable for rafting)</li>\n	<li>Long sleeved shirt to wear under your life vest to keep the sun off, preferably a quick-dry, synthetic fiber</li>\n	<li>Baseball cap (or similar) to wear under your helmet to keep the sun off</li>\n	<li>Wide-brimmed sun hat to wear on the bank</li>\n	<li>Sunglasses</li>\n	<li>Chums for fastening your sunglasses</li>\n	<li>Eye glasses or contact lenses (disposable lenses are ideal) - please let your guide know if you wear glasses in advance of your trip</li>\n	<li>Nalgene or other sturdy water bottle</li>\n	<li>Carabiner for fastening water bottle to your boat</li>\n	<li>Thermal top - meadium weight to heavyweight Capilene or polypropylene is the best choice</li>\n	<li>Waterproof sunscreen and lip balm (minimum SPF15)</li>\n	<li>Lightweight long trousers</li>\n	<li>Lightweight long sleeved shirt</li>\n	<li>Fleece jacket or sweater</li>\n	<li>Ladies, please bring a long skirt or sarong to wear in the company of locals or while visiting holy places</li>\n	<li>Shoes or boots for exploring off the river</li>\n	<li>Toiletries: toothbrush, toothpaste, biodegradable soap, shampoo, etc.</li>\n	<li>Moisturizer</li>\n	<li>Hand wipes or hand sanitizer</li>\n	<li>3-season sleeping bag and thermo rest sleeping mat if you prefer to use your own (we provide a complementary set upon request)</li>\n	<li>Travel pillow</li>\n	<li>Small pack towel</li>\n	<li>Headlamp or hand torch with spare batteries</li>\n	<li>Insect repellent</li>\n	<li>Any medications you may be taking</li>\n</ul>\n[tg_header title="What to Bring:"]\n<ul>\n	<li>A book or journal for recording river memories and inspirations</li>\n	<li>Sketchpad</li>\n	<li>Photographic, GOPRO, or video equipment. We recommend bringing your own waterproof casing and a cleaning kit as we will be camping in the sand. Don''t forget a spare memory card or plenty of film, as well as spare batteries.</li>\n	<li>Waterproof disposable camera to document the "action" on the raft</li>\n	<li>Pocket knife or multi-tool</li>\n	<li>iPod or other portable music device (your guide will pack the speakers)</li>\n	<li>Binoculars if you are a bird watcher</li>\n	<li>In short, we advise you to pack as light as possible, without skimping on the essentials.</li>\n</ul>\n[tg_header title="Personal Spending:"]\n<ul>\n	<li>The only money you will need on the excursion is for meals in town, souvenirs, personal items and the beer kitty for the raft trip if you drink. ATMs are available in larger towns.</li>\n	<li>If you wish to pass on a gratuity to your team, we leave this entirely up to you, but kindly suggest that if you do choose to give, give to the group as a whole so that the team can share with those who are working behind the scenes to make your trip complete.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Seti River Adventure', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '3374-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-07-22 12:50:42', '2016-07-22 12:50:42', '', 3374, 'http://nepalayaexplorer.com/2016/06/20/3374-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
