(3398, 3, '2016-08-07 13:21:22', '2016-08-07 13:21:22', '[tg_header title="A Classic Extreme Whitewater Adventure" subtitle="(bring your big-boy pants)"]\r\n\r\nExperience the thrills of world-renowned Nepali Whitewater with <strong>Madness Marsyangdi Express</strong>, Napalaya Explorer’s classic extreme rafting adventure. Draining off the northern slopes of Mt. Annapurna, the Marsyangdi has been described as “nonstop slalom.” The river is steep, technical, and not to be underestimated. This thrilling whitewater adventure offers crystal clear water and beautiful views of the Himalayas.\r\n\r\nIf you are looking for the most exciting whitewater adventure in Nepal and want to escape the crowds, Madness Marsyangdi Express is your best option. The Marsyangdi offers nonstop fast-flowing technical rapids. The river demands a skillful and energetic guide and participants who accept the challenge both physically and mentally.\r\n\r\nActivities require high physical output. Participants should be comfortable maintaining short bursts of high physical activity over the course of the day. Previous whitewater experience is recommended.\r\n\r\n[tg_header title="Quick Look" subtitle="Adventure Overview"]\r\n\r\n<strong>Best Season: </strong>February - May, mid. October - January\r\n<strong>Trip Duration: </strong>3 days (2 nights) from Kathmandu (Available as a 1-day upon request)\r\n<b>Difficulty: </b>Grade 4+ / 5\r\n<strong>River Volume</strong><strong>: </strong>800 cms / 2800 cfs in November\r\n<strong>Distance: </strong>60 km\r\n<strong>Skill Level:</strong> Adventurers, rafters, experienced kayakers, bold outdoor enthusiasts\r\n<strong>Put-in: </strong>Bulbulle\r\n<strong>Take-out: </strong>Turture\r\n<strong>Transportation:</strong> Private bus (7 hrs from Kathmandu, 4 hrs from Pokhara)\r\n<strong>Activities: </strong>Rafting\r\n<strong>Group Size: </strong>6 - 12 people\r\n<strong>Accommodations: </strong>Tented camping\r\n\r\n[tg_header title="Adventure Program"]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title="Day 1:" place="Kathmandu to Bulbulle"]\r\n\r\nAfter a hearty breakfast at one of the Kathmandu’s finer restaurants, we start our drive to the Marsyangdi River. On the way you will enjoy the view of the Himalayas, hillside terraced rice paddies, green lush forest, creeks and rivers. Stopping for lunch, we continue upstream along the Marsyangdi, taking the same route as trekkers heading towards the famous Annapurna Circuit.\r\n\r\nIn Bulbulle, we settle into one of the best campsites in the world. Sculpted into a Marsyangdi river bank, Nepalaya Explorer’s Marsyangdi camp offers views of the mountains and lush vegetation on the other side of the river. Behind our tents, on our side of the river, picturesque ethnic villages are nestled amidst fields of carefully-tended crops. Enjoy the evening sunset with a glass of wine or hot cup of tea, and after dinner, watch the millions of stars revolve in the Nepali night sky or bright full moon night.\r\n\r\n[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title="Day 2" place="Marsyangdi Rier"]\r\n\r\nFollowing a delicious, filling breakfast prepared by your guides, it’s time to get ready for the river. Once the Head Guide has fitted you out with your river gear, each guide takes his or her crew in hand to devote some time to instruction, teaching paddle strokes and technique, and offering tips to help you stay in the raft in serious whitewater. For anyone who missed a point in the previous lesson, there is also a lesson on swimming in whitewater, including how to use your flotation device, what to do with your feet, and how to negotiate rocks – or your friends – in mid current. The guides also give pointers on what to look out for on the river (such as that innocuous looking rise in the water that hides a hole, or the way you can use a pillow of water rebounding off a rock to push the raft where you want it to go). Also, the lead safety kayaker will devote some time to explain how you get rescue and help from them when’s you pup out from raft, they are quick, fast, friendly and calm you down in panicking condition and bring back to your raft by giving you free and safe ride through rapid so they are your Last Resort (please note that they are looking for the most happiest person, the reason behind is if you are panicking you will create the problem to them so keep SMILE to get rescue first). Nepalaya Explorer guides and kayakers are professionals who have devoted their lives to learning and running rivers. Under their careful tutelage, the raft crews learn to work as a team in order to navigate the challenging rapids ahead.\r\n\r\nOnce on the river, the crews are almost immediately in the thick of the action. Just as you are becoming tired, a leisurely riverside lunch break is just what the doctor ordered for restoring energy. Then we put back on the river for several more hours of thrilling whitewater before reaching the second camp.\r\n\r\n[/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_program title="Day 3" place="Marsyangdi - Takeout"]\r\n\r\nAfter a hearty breakfast, we start all over again. Gear on and get ready for our final day of heart-racing Madness Marsyangdi. We scout some of the challenging rapid to identify the safe and fun line, and perhaps portage a few if necessary. Lunch is prepared at the take-out by the road support crew, and then onward to the next adventure![/tg_program]\r\n\r\n[tg_header title="Price Includes:"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Licensed English-speaking local guides and safety kayakers, highly trained and safety certified to international standards in: Rescue 3 WRT, Nepal Red Cross CPR, High Peak First Aid, International Wilderness First-Aid, IRF trained, and highly knowledgable about the local area</li>\r\n	<li>High-quality, ISO certified rafting and kayaking equipment and full personal outfitting, including: paddles, helmets, PFDs (life jackets) dry tops, wetsuits (youth sizes available), dry bags, and pelican boxes for valuables such as cameras</li>\r\n	<li>Two nights at a *** hotel in Kathmandu, one day sightseeing in Kathmandu, airport pickup and drop-off</li>\r\n	<li>Camping accommodation, including: shelters, personal tents, air mattresses, sleeping bags, pillow, picnic umbrella, table and chairs, toilet tents</li>\r\n	<li>Three meals daily: a hearty breakfast, leisurely lunch, and dinner with a complementary glass of wine. While on the river, guides prepare traditional Nepali and western cuisine, made with fresh, organic ingredients.</li>\r\n	<li>Complementary beverages, including bottled water</li>\r\n	<li>Round trip transportation via private car</li>\r\n	<li>River permits</li>\r\n	<li>Village sightseeing</li>\r\n	<li>Adventure Industry standard first aid kits</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[tg_header title="Price Does Not Include:"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>International flights and associated taxes</li>\r\n	<li>Unrelated transportation, visas, travel documents, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Items of personal nature (toiletries, clothing, camera, etc.)</li>\r\n	<li>Alcohol and junk food</li>\r\n	<li>Bottled mineral water</li>\r\n	<li>Tips for porters and guides</li>\r\n	<li>Travel and health insurance</li>\r\n	<li>Photos - Professional trip photos may be available at a small additional charge. Please inquire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[tg_header title="Packing Aid:"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Your sense of adventure (and humor!)</li>\r\n	<li>River shorts or swim costume</li>\r\n	<li>Chacos or similar sandals that secure your heal (trainers or sneakers are also suitable for rafting)</li>\r\n	<li>Long sleeved shirt to wear under your life vest to keep the sun off, preferably a quick-dry, synthetic fiber</li>\r\n	<li>Baseball cap (or similar) to wear under your helmet to keep the sun off</li>\r\n	<li>Wide-brimmed sun hat to wear on the bank</li>\r\n	<li>Sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Chums for fastening your sunglasses</li>\r\n	<li>Eye glasses or contact lenses (disposable lenses are ideal) - please let your guide know if you wear glasses in advance of your trip</li>\r\n	<li>Nalgene or